{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-af6ed083757a9717", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tRT-Tango: Real-Time Distributed Binaural Speech Enhancement for\n2\tLow-Power Hearing Aid Devices\n3\tZahra Benslimane ID 1,2 , Pierre Chouteau1 , Martyna Poreba ID 1 , Fabrice Auzanneau ID 1 , Michal\n4\tSzczepanski ID 1 , Fabian Chersi ID 1 , Romain Serizel ID 2\n5\t1\n6\t\n7\t2\n8\t\n9\tUniversité Paris-Saclay, CEA, List, F-91120 Palaiseau, France\n10\tUniversité de Lorraine, CNRS, Inria, LORIA, F-54000 Nancy, France\n11\tzahra-hafida.benslimane@cea.fr\n12\t\n13\tarXiv:2607.01834v1 [cs.SD] 2 Jul 2026\n14\t\n15\tAbstract\n16\tReal-time binaural speech enhancement is constrained by latency, computational cost, and inter-device communication,\n17\tyet existing efficient solutions predominantly address singlechannel settings. In this paper, we introduce RT-Tango, a\n18\treal-time distributed binaural speech enhancement framework\n19\tdesigned for streaming on resource-constrained platforms and\n20\tspecifically for hearing aids. RT-Tango relies on a two-stage\n21\tdistributed architecture combining perceptually motivated ERB\n22\tfeature compression, lightweight grouped recurrent mask estimation, and temporal sparsification to reduce computational\n23\tcost. Stringent latency constraints are addressed by decoupling\n24\tspectral resolution from algorithmic delay using an asymmetric STFT, together with causal recurrent inference and online\n25\testimation of spatial statistics. Experimental results show that\n26\tRT-Tango achieves competitive speech enhancement while significantly reducing MACs operations and functioning at ultralow latencies as low as 8 ms.\n27\tIndex Terms: speech enhancement, distributed, binaural, lowlatency, real-time, hearing aid\n28\t\n29\t1. Introduction\n30\tReal-time speech enhancement (SE) in bandwidth-limited binaural and distributed systems, such as hearing aids, must operate\n31\tunder strict latency and computational constraints. Each device\n32\tprocesses audio locally, exchanging only minimal information,\n33\twhich places strong limitations on model complexity and communication. Addressing SE under these joint constraints is essential for practical on-device deployment.\n34\tOne line of research focuses on reducing the computational\n35\tcost of on-device SE through neural model compression, typically combining structured pruning and quantization to reduce\n36\tmemory use and computational complexity [1, 2, 3]. Hardwareoriented studies further show that not only the model’s sparsity level but also its structure critically impact the throughputmemory-quality trade-off on embedded platforms [4]. However, SE models are particularly sensitive to aggressive quantization due to their regression-based objectives, which amplifies quantization noise and hinders full integer deployment [5].\n37\tThis has motivated the search for alternative solutions, such as\n38\thardware-aware mixed-precision inference [6] or distillationbased training strategies [7]. Complementary research explores\n39\tarchitectural efficiency: designing compact models that inherently require fewer operations. Grouped processing is attractive\n40\tfor SE, where feature maps are partitioned into small groups and\n41\tThis research was carried out with the support of the French National Research Agency as part of the REFINED project, “REal-time\n42\tartiFicial INtelligence for hEaring aiDs” (ANR21-CE19-0043).\n43\t\n44\tprocessed in parallel by tiny sub-networks that periodically exchange information [8, 9]. Other works reduce input dimensionality by sub-sampling [10] or using an Equivalent Rectangular\n45\tBandwidth (ERB)-scaled filterbank to compress the frequency\n46\trepresentations, as in GTCRN [11].\n47\tDespite these advances, most efficiency-driven approaches\n48\tfocus on single-microphone SE. In contrast, efficient multimicrophone methods remain comparatively underexplored,\n49\teven though they can effectively exploit spatial cues for improved noise reduction. Recent works have begun to address this gap by proposing computationally efficient multimicrophone architectures, either by decoupling spatial and\n50\tspectral processing [12] or by employing lightweight attention mechanisms to model spatial dependencies [13]. Nevertheless, these approaches typically incur higher computational\n51\tcost than ultra-lightweight monaural models and often assume\n52\ta centralized processing with access to all microphone signals.\n53\tIn practical binaural hearing-device systems, microphones are\n54\tdistributed across physically separated nodes, and centralized\n55\tprocessing would require continuous high-bandwidth wireless\n56\ttransmission, which is infeasible under severe energy and bandwidth constraints. To address this limitation, fully distributed\n57\tfusion-center-free signal processing frameworks have been explored to balance SE performance with bandwidth-efficient\n58\tinter-device communication [14, 15].\n59\tWhile prior work has demonstrated the feasibility of\n60\treduced-bandwidth distributed binaural SE [16], jointly achieving low latency and low computational complexity remains an\n61\topen challenge. To the best of our knowledge, no existing\n62\tapproach combines the required design elements within a distributed binaural framework under explicit real-time latency and\n63\tcomputational constraints. This paper addresses this gap by introducing RT-Tango, a binaural SE framework specifically designed for real-time deployment on resource-constrained hearing devices. Concretely, our framework relies on the following\n64\tefficiency-driven design choices:\n65\t• Perceptually motivated feature compression using an ERBscaled filterbank, reducing input dimensionality while preserving speech-relevant cues.\n66\t• Lightweight grouped recurrent mask estimation, enabling\n67\tparallel and partitioned processing to reduce computational\n68\tcost in distributed binaural settings.\n69\t• Decoupled frequency resolution and algorithmic latency reduction through an asymmetric STFT configuration tailored\n70\tfor streaming operations.\n71\t• Temporal sparsification for real-time inference, including\n72\tboth learned skip-RNN gating and fixed-rate frame reuse to\n73\treduce recurrent updates.\n74\t\n75\t\f2. Methodology\n76\tRT-Tango revisits the Tango framework [16] from a systemlevel perspective. This redesign is motivated by the stringent\n77\tconstraints of hearing aids, where strict causality, ultra-low latency, limited memory, and low-power embedded hardware are\n78\tcritical requirements. Rather than introducing isolated optimizations, RT-Tango adopts complementary architectural and\n79\talgorithmic design principles detailed in the following sections.\n80\t\n81\tStage 1\n82\t\n83\tSTFT\n84\tSTFT\n85\t\n86\tRear R\n87\t\n88\tRear L\n89\t\n90\tFront R\n91\t\n92\tFront L\n93\t\n94\tSTFT\n95\tSTFT\n96\t\n97\tSN-DNN\n98\tERB Features\n99\t\n100\tSN-DNN\n101\tERB Features\n102\t\n103\tGRNN+FC\n104\t\n105\tGRNN+FC\n106\t\n107\tInv ERB\n108\t\n109\tInv ERB\n110\t\n111\tSDW-MWF\n112\t\n113\tSDW-MWF\n114\t\n115\t2.1. Baseline\n116\tTango serves as our baseline due to its two-stage distributed architecture (illustrated in Figure 1) and proven effectiveness in\n117\tspatially unconstrained microphone configurations [16]. Each\n118\tear-node independently estimates speech and noise masks using\n119\ta Single-Node DNN (SN-DNN) and computes a Speech Distortion Weighted Multichannel Wiener Filter (SDW-MWF) [17].\n120\tThis produces an ear-specific compressed signal, which is transmitted to the contra-lateral ear-node. Then, a Multi-Node DNN\n121\t(MN-DNN) refines the masks using both local signals and exchanged representations, from which a final SDW-MWF generates the enhanced binaural output. In its original formulation,\n122\thowever, the baseline imposes no latency or complexity constraints.\n123\t2.2. Lightweight neural mask estimation\n124\tTo reduce the computational cost of this distributed binaural\n125\tprocessing, RT-Tango improves the efficiency in neural mask\n126\testimation by means of perceptually driven feature compression, grouped modeling of localized spectral dependencies, and\n127\ttemporal sparsification, while preserving the characteristic twostage distributed spatial filtering framework of Tango.\n128\t2.2.1. Feature compression\n129\tThe ERB representation is used as the front-end for both neural mask estimation networks (indicated as SN-DNN and MNDNN in Figure 1). This perceptually motivated transformation\n130\treduces spectral resolution at high frequencies, where human\n131\tauditory sensitivity is coarser, while preserving finer resolution\n132\tat lower frequencies that carry most speech energy and cues. By\n133\taligning the features with perceptual frequency scaling, ERB\n134\tcompression reduces the input dimensionality of the mask estimators, lowering the number of parameters and operations in\n135\tsubsequent layers. The estimated masks are then mapped back\n136\tto the linear-frequency domain using an inverse ERB transformation to restore the spectral resolution required for filtering.\n137\t2.2.2. Grouped RNN mask estimation\n138\tThe mask estimation networks of RT-Tango implement a\n139\tgrouped recurrent neural network (GRNN) to reduce computational complexity while preserving modeling capacity [18].\n140\tThis choice is motivated by the localized nature of spectral\n141\tdependencies in speech signals and the need to control recurrent computational complexity. Localized recurrent modeling within frequency sub-bands is consistent with common\n142\tSE assumptions as spectral dependencies are typically stronger\n143\twithin nearby frequency regions. Since the computational\n144\tcost of recurrent layers scales approximately quadratically as\n145\tO(H 2 ) with the hidden state dimension H, partitioning the\n146\tfeature space into G groups of size H/G, the total recurrent\n147\tcomplexity becomes G · O((H/G)2 ) = O(H 2 /G), making\n148\tit significantly lower compared to a full-band RNN. Although\n149\t\n150\tMN-DNN\n151\tERB Features\n152\t\n153\tMN-DNN\n154\tERB Features\n155\t\n156\tGRNN+FC\n157\t\n158\tGRNN+FC\n159\t\n160\tInv ERB\n161\t\n162\tInv ERB\n163\t\n164\tSDW-MWF\n165\tStage 2\n166\t\n167\tiSTFT\n168\t\n169\tiSTFT\n170\t\n171\tOut R\n172\t\n173\tOut L\n174\t\n175\tSDW-MWF\n176\t\n177\tFigure 1: Block diagram of RT-Tango. It preserves Tango’s twostage processing scheme while introducing additional or modified modules focused on efficiency (highlighted in yellow) and\n178\tlow-latency streaming (in italics).\n179\t\n180\tthe processing is performed independently within each group,\n181\tcross-band dependencies are captured through a representation\n182\trearrangement mechanism [18], enabling cross-band information exchange and global spectral modeling.\n183\t2.2.3. Temporal sparsification\n184\tTo further reduce the computational load of high-rate real-time\n185\tstreaming, RT-Tango exploits temporal redundancy in the input signal using skip inference strategies. Instead of performing a neural inference at every frame, the mask estimation networks reuse previously estimated masks when the input signal\n186\texhibits limited temporal variation. This temporal sparsification reduces the mask’s update frequency and thus the overall\n187\tcomputational cost during streaming inference. In RT-Tango,\n188\twe define Fixed-Rate Skipping (FRS), as a strategy that executes the mask estimator at a predefined interval and reuses\n189\tpreviously estimated masks in between. We compare this with\n190\tlearned skip gates [3, 19], where a gating mechanism dynamically decides whether to update the recurrent state at each frame\n191\t(see Section 3.2.2).\n192\t2.3. Low-latency streaming\n193\tTo support low-latency streaming, we use an asymmetric STFT\n194\tconfiguration [20, 21]. We use a long analysis window (aW)\n195\tthat preserves the frequency resolution and a shorter synthesis window (sW) to reduce the reconstruction latency, enabling\n196\tlow-latency real-time streaming. The spatial covariance matrices (SCM) required by the SDW-MWF are updated online using\n197\ta recursive exponential moving average (EMA). Under these\n198\tstreaming constraints, the system operates as RT-Tango-OS.\n199\t\n200\t\fTable 1: Model comparison with left/right ear scores. Computational cost is reported in MMACs/s and decomposed into DNN and\n201\tSDW-MWF components. A hop size of 16 ms corresponds to ≈ 62 STFT frames/s, while 4 ms corresponds to ≈ 250 STFT frames/s.\n202\tSI-SAR is not reported for the unprocessed mixture, where no processing artifacts are present.\n203\tSTFT\n204\tModel\n205\t\n206\tHop\n207\t\n208\tTotal\n209\t\n210\tMMACs/s ↓\n211\t\n212\tSI-SIR ↑\n213\t\n214\tSI-SDR ↑\n215\t\n216\tSI-SAR ↑\n217\t\n218\tSTOI ↑\n219\t\n220\tPESQ ↑\n221\t\n222\tDNN\n223\t\n224\tL\n225\t\n226\tR\n227\t\n228\tL\n229\t\n230\tR\n231\t\n232\tL\n233\t\n234\tL\n235\t\n236\tL\n237\t\n238\tSDW-MWF\n239\t\n240\tR\n241\t\n242\tR\n243\t\n244\tR\n245\t\n246\t−\n247\t\n248\t−\n249\t\n250\t−\n251\t\n252\t−\n253\t\n254\t0.0\n255\t\n256\t−4.0\n257\t\n258\t−0.6\n259\t\n260\t−4.6\n261\t\n262\t−\n263\t\n264\t−\n265\t\n266\t0.68\n267\t\n268\t0.56\n269\t\n270\t1.14\n271\t\n272\t1.10\n273\t\n274\tTango\n275\tGTCRN\n276\tGTCRN\n277\t\n278\t16 ms\n279\t16 ms\n280\t4 ms\n281\t\n282\t605.98\n283\t48.98\n284\t197.5\n285\t\n286\t604.5\n287\t48.98\n288\t197.5\n289\t\n290\t1.48\n291\t−\n292\t−\n293\t\n294\t20.8\n295\t16.1\n296\t16.6\n297\t\n298\t24.1\n299\t14.1\n300\t13.8\n301\t\n302\t4.2\n303\t5.6\n304\t6.0\n305\t\n306\t4.4\n307\t3.7\n308\t4.0\n309\t\n310\t4.7\n311\t6.4\n312\t6.7\n313\t\n314\t4.7\n315\t4.5\n316\t5.0\n317\t\n318\t0.83\n319\t0.76\n320\t0.79\n321\t\n322\t0.84\n323\t0.69\n324\t0.71\n325\t\n326\t1.61\n327\t1.47\n328\t1.52\n329\t\n330\t1.64\n331\t1.34\n332\t1.36\n333\t\n334\tTango-RNN\n335\t+ GRNNSN=8\n336\tMN=2 ⋆\n337\t\n338\t16 ms\n339\t16 ms\n340\t\n341\t67.20\n342\t18.22\n343\t\n344\t65.72\n345\t16.74\n346\t\n347\t1.48\n348\t1.48\n349\t\n350\t21.6\n351\t21.3\n352\t\n353\t25.0\n354\t24.8\n355\t\n356\t4.7\n357\t4.5\n358\t\n359\t5.0\n360\t4.8\n361\t\n362\t5.2\n363\t5.1\n364\t\n365\t5.2\n366\t5.0\n367\t\n368\t0.84\n369\t0.84\n370\t\n371\t0.85\n372\t0.84\n373\t\n374\t1.66\n375\t1.66\n376\t\n377\t1.70\n378\t1.70\n379\t\n380\tRT-Tango (ours)\n381\tRT-Tango-OS (ours)\n382\t\n383\t4 ms\n384\t4 ms\n385\t\n386\t33.41\n387\t35.14\n388\t\n389\t28.08\n390\t28.08\n391\t\n392\t5.33\n393\t7.01\n394\t\n395\t20.8\n396\t20.5\n397\t\n398\t24.6\n399\t24.7\n400\t\n401\t4.4\n402\t2.9\n403\t\n404\t4.7\n405\t3.8\n406\t\n407\t5.0\n408\t3.4\n409\t\n410\t5.0\n411\t4.0\n412\t\n413\t0.84\n414\t0.80\n415\t\n416\t0.84\n417\t0.82\n418\t\n419\t1.66\n420\t1.54\n421\t\n422\t1.71\n423\t1.63\n424\t\n425\tUnprocessed\n426\t\n427\t3. Experiments\n428\t3.1. Experimental setup\n429\tModels were trained on a simulated binaural dataset following the protocol of Monir et al. [22], which utilized a fourmicrophone hearing aid configuration with two microphones\n430\tper ear. Clean speech from LibriSpeech [23] was mixed with\n431\tspeech-shaped noise and real-world environmental noise. Evaluation was conducted on a subset of the BinauRec1 binaural\n432\tdataset [24], comprising 1,200 mixtures generated using measured room impulse responses (RIRs) acquired using a portable\n433\thearing laboratory (PHL) [25] with behind-the-ear hearing aids\n434\tmounted on a dummy head. We considered configurations\n435\twhere the target speech source was located in front and the noise\n436\tpositioned at 45◦ and 90◦ to the right of the target, respectively.\n437\tThis results in a lower SIR at the right ear than at the left ear.\n438\tDry signals are mixed at input SNRs of −5, 0, and 5 dB, before\n439\tbeing convolved with the RIR.\n440\tEnhancement performance was evaluated using scaleinvariant objective metrics (SI-SDR, SI-SIR, and SI-SAR), reported in dB [26], together with perceptual measures PESQ [27]\n441\tand STOI [28]. Processing cost is reported in terms of MACs\n442\teither per second or per frame, measured for one processing\n443\tnode. Reported MACs include the DNN mask estimators, ERB\n444\tand inverse-ERB transformations, and SDW-MWF processing,\n445\twhile FFT and iFFT operations are excluded.\n446\tAlongside the original CNN-based Tango implementation,\n447\twe consider a causal variant, Tango-RNN, in which both the\n448\tSN-DNN and MN-DNN are implemented using two stacked\n449\tstateful RNN layers with 128 hidden units, followed by a fully\n450\tconnected layer. We also include a lightweight neural baseline\n451\tby adapting GTCRN [11] to the distributed setting, deploying\n452\tone instance per node. Each instance processes the four microphone signals as input and applies its estimated mask to the\n453\tlocal reference channel, preserving a distributed per-node architecture.\n454\tModels were implemented in PyTorch and trained with an\n455\tAdam optimizer (lr = 10−3 ), by minimizing the mean squared\n456\terror between the estimated time–frequency mask and the target\n457\tideal ratio mask. Training audio used a 32 ms STFT analysis\n458\twindow with a 16 ms hop for grouped ablations, FRS, and RTTango/RT-Tango-OS. For learned skipping and GTCRN (4 ms),\n459\tthe hop was reduced to 4 ms to match RT-Tango’s frame rate.\n460\tRT-Tango replaces the recurrent layers in Tango-RNN with\n461\t1 Online: https://zenodo.org/records/7256984\n462\t\n463\tGRNNs to reduce its computational cost. We use G = 8 groups\n464\tfor the SN-DNN and G = 2 groups for the MN-DNN. Temporal sparsification is implemented using FRS, with update rates\n465\tof 1/4 for the SN-DNN and 1/2 for the MN-DNN, corresponding to one inference every four and two frames, respectively.\n466\tAll results, except those obtained for RT-Tango-OS, were\n467\tcomputed using SCMs estimated over entire utterances. RTTango-OS instead uses recursive SCM updates with a forgetting factor α = 0.995, applied every 8 frames at the 4 ms input\n468\trate, resulting in an effective update interval of 32 ms (≈ 31\n469\tupdates/s). As online SCM estimation requires an adaptation\n470\tperiod, RT-Tango-OS was evaluated in steady state by repeating each mixture a sufficient number of times to allow for convergence. The metrics are computed on the final repetition (see\n471\tSection 3.2.4).\n472\tTable 2: Ablation study on grouping strategies. The reported\n473\tMMACs per frame are computed exclusively for the DNNs.\n474\tDNN (SN+MN)\n475\tModel\n476\t\n477\tSI-SDR\n478\t\n479\tSI-SAR\n480\t\n481\tMMACs / frame\n482\t\n483\tL\n484\t\n485\tR\n486\t\n487\tL\n488\t\n489\tR\n490\t\n491\tTango-RNN\n492\t\n493\t1.06\n494\t\n495\t4.7\n496\t\n497\t5.0\n498\t\n499\t5.2\n500\t\n501\t5.2\n502\t\n503\t+ GRNNSN=2\n504\t+ GRNNSN=8\n505\t\n506\t0.69\n507\t0.59\n508\t\n509\t4.7\n510\t4.7\n511\t\n512\t4.9\n513\t4.9\n514\t\n515\t5.2\n516\t5.1\n517\t\n518\t5.2\n519\t5.1\n520\t\n521\t+ GRNNMN=2\n522\t+ GRNNMN=8\n523\t\n524\t0.74\n525\t0.64\n526\t\n527\t4.7\n528\t3.8\n529\t\n530\t4.9\n531\t4.1\n532\t\n533\t5.2\n534\t4.2\n535\t\n536\t5.1\n537\t4.3\n538\t\n539\t3.2. Results\n540\tIn Table 1, we report the results of RT-Tango and its streaming\n541\tvariant RT-Tango-OS, and compare them to the Tango baseline,\n542\tTango-RNN, and GTCRN. Compared to GTCRN, both Tango\n543\tand Tango-RNN achieve consistently higher PESQ, STOI, and\n544\tSI-SIR scores across both ears. Although GTCRN slightly outperforms them in SI-SDR and SI-SAR on the less noise-affected\n545\tleft node, Tango-based approaches show a more balanced leftright behavior due to their two-stage mechanism. This interaural balance is particularly desirable in hearing-aid applications\n546\tfor stable spatial perception and listening comfort.\n547\tTango-RNN reduces Tango’s complexity to 67.2 MMAC/s,\n548\twhile RT-Tango reaches 33.4 MMAC/s despite operating at a\n549\thigher frame rate. Under identical conditions, RT-Tango is\n550\tnearly six times more efficient than GTCRN (197.5 MMAC/s).\n551\tThis robustness to compression stems from its hybrid architec-\n552\t\n553\t\fTable 3: Temporal sparsification in the SN-DNN of (⋆): performance and per-frame cost for updated (w/o skip) and nonupdated (w/skip) frames.\n554\t\n555\tTable 5: Effect of window length and type on enhancement performance, evaluated using RT-Tango.\n556\tSI-SDR\n557\t\n558\tModel\n559\t\n560\tSI-SDR\n561\t\n562\tSI-SAR\n563\t\n564\taW\n565\t\n566\tsW\n567\t\n568\tWindow\n569\t\n570\tL\n571\t\n572\tR\n573\t\n574\tL\n575\t\n576\tR\n577\t\n578\tw/o Skip w/ Skip\n579\t\n580\tL\n581\t\n582\tR\n583\t\n584\tL\n585\t\n586\tR\n587\t\n588\t32\n589\t\n590\t32\n591\t\n592\tsqrtHann\n593\t\n594\t4.4\n595\t\n596\t4.7\n597\t\n598\t5.0\n599\t\n600\t5.0\n601\t\n602\t4.8\n603\t\n604\t5.1\n605\t\n606\t5.0\n607\t\n608\t32\n609\t32\n610\t32\n611\t\n612\t8\n613\t8\n614\t4\n615\t\n616\tsqrtHann\n617\tasyHann\n618\tasyHann\n619\t\n620\t1.2\n621\t3.7\n622\t3.4\n623\t\n624\t1.8\n625\t4.3\n626\t4.0\n627\t\n628\t1.4\n629\t4.3\n630\t3.9\n631\t\n632\t1.9\n633\t4.5\n634\t4.1\n635\t\n636\tSN-DNN of (⋆)\n637\t\n638\t0.09\n639\t\n640\t−\n641\t\n642\t4.5\n643\t\n644\t(⋆) + FRS 1/2\n645\t(⋆) + FRS 1/4\n646\t(⋆) + SkipRNN [19]\n647\t(⋆) + TinyLSTM [3]\n648\t\n649\t0.09\n650\t0.09\n651\t0.09\n652\t0.12\n653\t\n654\t0\n655\t0\n656\t0.01\n657\t0.09\n658\t\n659\t4.4 4.7 5.1 5.0\n660\t4.3 4.6 5.0 4.9\n661\t4.4 4.3 5.0 4.6\n662\t4.3 4.4 5.0 4.7\n663\t\n664\tTable 4: Temporal sparsification in the MN-DNN of (⋆): performance and per-frame cost for updated (w/o skip) and nonupdated (w/skip) frames.\n665\t\n666\tModel\n667\t\n668\tSI-SAR\n669\t\n670\tMMACs / frame\n671\t\n672\tMMACs / frame\n673\t\n674\tSI-SDR\n675\t\n676\tSI-SAR\n677\t\n678\tw/o Skip w/ Skip\n679\t\n680\tL\n681\t\n682\tR\n683\t\n684\tL\n685\t\n686\t4.8\n687\t\n688\t5.1 5.0\n689\t\n690\tR\n691\t\n692\tMN-DNN of (⋆)\n693\t\n694\t0.18\n695\t\n696\t−\n697\t\n698\t4.5\n699\t\n700\t(⋆) + FRS 1/2\n701\t(⋆) + FRS 1/4\n702\t(⋆) + SkipRNN [19]\n703\t(⋆) + TinyLSTM [3]\n704\t\n705\t0.18\n706\t0.18\n707\t0.18\n708\t0.21\n709\t\n710\t0\n711\t0\n712\t0.02\n713\t0.07\n714\t\n715\t4.4 4.8 5.1 5.1\n716\t4.3 4.8 4.8 5.0\n717\t3.8 4.7 4.5 5.0\n718\t3.3 4.6 3.9 4.8\n719\t\n720\tture, where neural networks guide the spatial filter rather than\n721\tdirectly reconstructing the signal.\n722\tRT-Tango-OS enables strictly causal streaming with an algorithmic latency of 8 ms, through the asymmetric STFT and\n723\tonline SDW-MWF updates, resulting in a slight but expected\n724\tperformance degradation relative to offline RT-Tango. RTTango-OS requires 0.49 MMACs per frame (0.27 MMACs\n725\tfor the DNN and 0.22 MMACs for the SDW-MWF update).\n726\tWith the proposed temporal sparsification, it corresponds to\n727\t35.14 MMACs/s at ≈250 frames/s. Without sparsification\n728\t(not reported here), the computational cost would reach 124\n729\tMMACs/s. The RT-Tango-OS configuration results from the\n730\tprogressive design choices described in Section 2, whose individual contributions are analyzed in the ablation studies below.\n731\t3.2.1. Impact of Grouped Recurrent Modeling\n732\tGrouping applied independently to SN-DNN and MN-DNN reveals different behaviors (Table 2). Grouping the SN-DNN significantly reduces cost with negligible impact on quality. Using 8 groups on SN-DNN lowers the total DNN (SN+MN)\n733\tcomplexity from 1.06 to 0.59 MMAC/frame while maintaining\n734\tSI-SDR at 4.7/4.9 dB and preserving PESQ/STOI. In contrast,\n735\tMN-DNN is more sensitive to grouping. While MN=2-GRNN\n736\tpreserves performance, MN=8-GRNN degrades SI-SDR and\n737\tSI-SAR by around 0.8-1 dB. These results justify the combined\n738\tgrouping strategy (SN=8, MN=2), marked with (⋆) in Table 1.\n739\t3.2.2. Effect of temporal sparsification via skip inference\n740\tTables 3 and 4 evaluate temporal sparsification for the SNDNN and MN-DNN stages. For SN-DNN, FRS preserves performance within 0.2 dB of the baseline for both 1/2 and 1/4\n741\tconfigurations while eliminating computation on non-updated\n742\tframes. Learned skipping relies on a gating mechanism that\n743\tmust be evaluated at every frame, introducing additional MACs.\n744\tLearned skipping achieves an effective skip ratio of 80%, but\n745\t\n746\tstill introduces minor degradation, primarily on the right channel. The MN-DNN is more sensitive to learned skipping; it\n747\treduces SI-SDR from 4.5 dB to 3.8 dB (SkipRNN [19]) and\n748\t3.3 dB (TinyLSTM [3]) on the left channel, whereas FRS maintains performance within 0.2 dB of the baseline. Given its stability and predictable computational savings, FRS is adopted in\n749\tthe RT-Tango configuration (SN 1/4, MN 1/2), corresponding\n750\tto 75% frame skipping in the SN-DNN and 50% in the MNDNN. At a 4 ms hop rate, this reduces the DNN cost from 67.5\n751\tMMACs/s without sparsification to 28.08 MMACs/s.\n752\t3.2.3. Analysis of the latency-quality trade-off\n753\tTable 5 analyzes the impact of reducing the synthesis window\n754\twhile keeping the analysis window fixed at 32 ms. These results are computed with batch (offline) SCMs to isolate the effect of the STFT configuration from online SCM estimation.\n755\tStandard square-root Hann windows degrade rapidly at short\n756\tsynthesis lengths. In contrast, the asymmetric Hann [21] configuration maintains better SI-SDR and SI-SAR at low latencies. An 8 ms synthesis window offers the most favorable compromise between delay and SE quality. Reducing the synthesis\n757\twindow to 4 ms further decreases latency but results in performance degradation. We therefore select the 8 ms asymmetric\n758\tHann synthesis window for RT-Tango-OS.\n759\t3.2.4. Online SCM matrix estimation and convergence\n760\tAs can be seen in Table 1, RT-Tango-OS achieves an SI-SIR\n761\tcomparable to the offline RT-Tango. However, due to the constraints imposed by low-latency streaming, the SI-SDR and SISAR show a slight decrease. This performance gap is first introduced by the asymmetric STFT configuration (Section 3.2.3),\n762\tand is then amplified by the requirements of online SCM estimation. Despite this, RT-Tango-OS maintains STOI and PESQ\n763\tvalues close to GTCRN at the same high frame rate, while still\n764\tbeing significantly more computationally efficient. This indicates that although strictly online SCM estimation affects reconstruction, the resulting speech intelligibility and perceived\n765\tquality remain competitive with our baselines.\n766\t\n767\t4. Conclusions\n768\tThis paper introduced RT-Tango, a distributed binaural SE\n769\tframework designed to satisfy the stringent real-time, latency,\n770\tand computational constraints of modern hearing devices. By\n771\trevisiting the Tango architecture through complementary architectural and signal-processing optimizations, RT-Tango significantly reduces computational complexity while preserving enhancement performance and interaural balance. In addition, RTTango-OS, its strictly causal streaming variant, operates with an\n772\talgorithmic latency of 8 ms, makes RT-Tango particularly well\n773\tsuited for practical deployment in modern binaural hearing aids.\n774\t\n775\t\f5. Generative AI Use Disclosure\n776\tThe authors used AI tools solely for language editing and clarity improvement. All scientific ideas, content, and results were\n777\tdeveloped and verified by the authors.\n778\t\n779\t6. References\n780\t[1] K. Tan and D. Wang, “Towards Model Compression for Deep\n781\tLearning Based Speech Enhancement,” IEEE/ACM Transactions\n782\ton Audio, Speech, and Language Processing, vol. 29, pp. 1785–\n783\t1794, 2021.\n784\t[2] J.-Y. Wu, C. Yu, S.-W. Fu, C.-T. Liu, S.-Y. Chien, and Y. Tsao,\n785\t“Increasing Compactness of Deep Learning Based Speech Enhancement Models With Parameter Pruning and Quantization\n786\tTechniques,” IEEE Signal Processing Letters, vol. 26, no. 12, pp.\n787\t1887–1891, 2019.\n788\t[3] I. Fedorov, M. Stamenovic, C. Jensen, L.-C. Yang, A. Mandell,\n789\tY. Gan, M. Mattina, and P. N. Whatmough, “TinyLSTMs: Efficient Neural Speech Enhancement for Hearing Aids,” in Interspeech, 2020, pp. 4054–4058.\n790\t[4] M. Stamenovic, N. L. Westhausen, L.-C. Yang, C. Jensen, and\n791\tA. Pawlicki, “Weight, Block or Unit? Exploring Sparsity Tradeoffs for Speech Enhancement on Tiny Neural Accelerators,” in\n792\tNeurIPS Workshop on Efficient Natural Language and Speech\n793\tProcessing (NeurIPS ENLSP), 2021.\n794\t[5] E. Cohen, H. V. Habi, and A. Netzer, “Towards Fully Quantized Neural Networks For Speech Enhancement,” in Interspeech,\n795\t2023, pp. 181–185.\n796\t[6] M. Rusci, M. Fariselli, M. Croome, F. Paci, and E. Flamand,\n797\t“Accelerating RNN-based Speech Enhancement on a Multi-Core\n798\tMCU with Mixed FP16-INT8 Post-Training Quantization,” in\n799\tEuropean Conference on Machine Learning and Principles and\n800\tPractice of Knowledge Discovery in Databases (ECML PKDD),\n801\t2022, pp. 606–617.\n802\t[7] E. Cohen, H. V. Habi, R. Peretz, and A. Netzer, “Fully Quantized\n803\tNeural Networks for Audio Source Separation,” IEEE Open Journal of Signal Processing, vol. 5, pp. 926–933, 2024.\n804\t[8] K. Tan and D. Wang, “Learning Complex Spectral Mapping With\n805\tGated Convolutional Recurrent Networks for Monaural Speech\n806\tEnhancement,” IEEE/ACM Transactions on Audio, Speech, and\n807\tLanguage Processing, vol. 28, pp. 380–390, 2020.\n808\t[9] Y. Luo, C. Han, and N. Mesgarani, “Ultra-Lightweight Speech\n809\tSeparation Via Group Communication,” in IEEE International\n810\tConference on Audio, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP),\n811\t2021, pp. 16–20.\n812\t[10] Z.-Q. Wang, S. Cornell, S. Choi, Y. Lee, B.-Y. Kim, and S. Watanabe, “FNeural Speech Enhancement with Very Low Algorithmic\n813\tLatency and Complexity via Integrated full- and sub-band Modeling,” in IEEE International Conference on Audio, Speech and\n814\tSignal Processing (ICASSP), 2023, pp. 1–5.\n815\t[11] X. Rong, T. Sun, X. Zhang, Y. Hu, C. Zhu, and J. Lu, “GTCRN: A\n816\tSpeech Enhancement Model Requiring Ultralow Computational\n817\tResources,” in IEEE International Conference on Audio, Speech\n818\tand Signal Processing (ICASSP), 2024, pp. 971–975.\n819\t[12] A. Pandey and J. Azcarreta, “Ultra low-compute complex spectral masking for multichannel speech enhancement,” in IEEE International Conference on Audio, Speech and Signal Processing\n820\t(ICASSP), 2025, pp. 1–5.\n821\t[13] Y. Zhang, H. Pei, W. Wang, and G. Huang, “LMFCA-Net: A\n822\tLightweight Model for Multi-Channel Speech Enhancement with\n823\tEfficient Narrow-Band and Cross-Band Attention,” in IEEE International Conference on Audio, Speech and Signal Processing\n824\t(ICASSP), 2025, pp. 1–5.\n825\t[14] A. Bertrand and M. Moonen, “Distributed Adaptive NodeSpecific Signal Estimation in Fully Connected Sensor Networks—Part II: Simultaneous and Asynchronous Node Updating,” IEEE Transactions on Signal Processing, vol. 58, no. 10,\n826\tpp. 5292–5306, 2010.\n827\t\n828\t[15] S. Doclo, M. Moonen, T. Van den Bogaert, and J. Wouters,\n829\t“Reduced-Bandwidth and Distributed MWF-Based Noise Reduction Algorithms for Binaural Hearing Aids,” IEEE Transactions\n830\ton Audio, Speech, and Language Processing, vol. 17, no. 1, pp.\n831\t38–51, 2009.\n832\t[16] N. Furnon, R. Serizel, S. Essid, and I. Illina, “DNN-Based Mask\n833\tEstimation for Distributed Speech Enhancement in Spatially Unconstrained Microphone Arrays,” IEEE/ACM Transactions on Audio, Speech, and Language Processing, vol. 29, pp. 2310–2323,\n834\t2021.\n835\t[17] S. Doclo, A. Spriet, J. Wouters, and M. Moonen, “Frequencydomain criterion for the speech distortion weighted multichannel\n836\twiener filter for robust noise reduction,” Speech Communication,\n837\tvol. 49, no. 7–8, p. 636–656, Jul. 2007.\n838\t[18] F. Gao, L. Wu, L. Zhao, T. Qin, X. Cheng, and T.-Y. Liu, “Efficient Sequence Learning with Group Recurrent Networks,” in\n839\tProceedings of the 2018 Conference of the North American Chapter of the Association for Computational Linguistics: Human Language Technologies, Volume 1 (Long Papers), M. Walker, H. Ji,\n840\tand A. Stent, Eds., Jun. 2018, pp. 799–808.\n841\t[19] V. Campos, B. Jou, X. G. i Nieto, J. Torres, and S.-F. Chang,\n842\t“Skip RNN: Learning to Skip State Updates in Recurrent Neural\n843\tNetworks,” in International Conference on Learning Representations, 2018.\n844\t[20] Z.-Q. Wang, G. Wichern, S. Watanabe, and J. Le Roux, “Stftdomain neural speech enhancement with very low algorithmic latency,” IEEE/ACM Transactions on Audio, Speech, and Language\n845\tProcessing, vol. 31, pp. 397–410, 2023.\n846\t[21] S. U. N. Wood and J. Rouat, “Unsupervised Low Latency Speech\n847\tEnhancement With RT-GCC-NMF,” IEEE Journal of Selected\n848\tTopics in Signal Processing, vol. 13, no. 2, p. 332–346, May 2019.\n849\t[22] N.-E. Monir, P. Magron, and R. Serizel, “Frequency-Weighted\n850\tTraining Losses for Phoneme-Level DNN-based Speech Enhancement,” in IEEE International Workshop on Multimedia Signal Processing (MMSP), 2025, pp. 310–315.\n851\t[23] V. Panayotov, G. Chen, D. Povey, and S. Khudanpur, “Librispeech: An ASR corpus based on public domain audio books,”\n852\tin IEEE International Conference on Audio, Speech and Signal\n853\tProcessing (ICASSP), 2015, pp. 5206–5210.\n854\t[24] L. Delebecque and R. Serizel, “BinauRec: A dataset to test the influence of the use of room impulse responses on binaural speech\n855\tenhancement,” in European Signal Processing Conference (EUSIPCO), 2023, pp. 126–130.\n856\t[25] C. Pavlovic, R. Kassayan, S. R. Prakash, H. Kayser, V. Hohmann,\n857\tand A. Atamaniuk, “A high-fidelity multi-channel portable platform for development of novel algorithms for assistive listening\n858\twearables,” The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America, vol.\n859\t146, pp. 2878–2878, 2019.\n860\t[26] J. L. Roux, S. Wisdom, H. Erdogan, and J. R. Hershey, “SDR\n861\t– Half-baked or Well Done?” in IEEE International Conference\n862\ton Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP), 2019, pp.\n863\t626–630.\n864\t[27] A. Rix, J. Beerends, M. Hollier, and A. Hekstra, “Perceptual evaluation of speech quality (PESQ)-a new method for speech quality\n865\tassessment of telephone networks and codecs,” in IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech, and Signal Processing\n866\t(ICASSP), vol. 2, 2001, pp. 749–752.\n867\t[28] C. H. Taal, R. C. Hendriks, R. Heusdens, and J. Jensen, “A shorttime objective intelligibility measure for time-frequency weighted\n868\tnoisy speech,” in IEEE International Conference on Acoustics,\n869\tSpeech and Signal Processing (ICASSP), 2010, pp. 4214–4217.\n870\t\n871\t\f\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "6dfca6d6-2dc7-42e7-895d-186d3cb497ea", "uuid": "6b38b924-f3c0-4117-b090-e550a7a30617", "timestamp": "2026-07-12T08:43:54.820Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/rttango.txt", "content": "RT-Tango: Real-Time Distributed Binaural Speech Enhancement for\nLow-Power Hearing Aid Devices\nZahra Benslimane ID 1,2 , Pierre Chouteau1 , Martyna Poreba ID 1 , Fabrice Auzanneau ID 1 , Michal\nSzczepanski ID 1 , Fabian Chersi ID 1 , Romain Serizel ID 2\n1\n\n2\n\nUniversité Paris-Saclay, CEA, List, F-91120 Palaiseau, France\nUniversité de Lorraine, CNRS, Inria, LORIA, F-54000 Nancy, France\nzahra-hafida.benslimane@cea.fr\n\narXiv:2607.01834v1 [cs.SD] 2 Jul 2026\n\nAbstract\nReal-time binaural speech enhancement is constrained by latency, computational cost, and inter-device communication,\nyet existing efficient solutions predominantly address singlechannel settings. In this paper, we introduce RT-Tango, a\nreal-time distributed binaural speech enhancement framework\ndesigned for streaming on resource-constrained platforms and\nspecifically for hearing aids. RT-Tango relies on a two-stage\ndistributed architecture combining perceptually motivated ERB\nfeature compression, lightweight grouped recurrent mask estimation, and temporal sparsification to reduce computational\ncost. Stringent latency constraints are addressed by decoupling\nspectral resolution from algorithmic delay using an asymmetric STFT, together with causal recurrent inference and online\nestimation of spatial statistics. Experimental results show that\nRT-Tango achieves competitive speech enhancement while significantly reducing MACs operations and functioning at ultralow latencies as low as 8 ms.\nIndex Terms: speech enhancement, distributed, binaural, lowlatency, real-time, hearing aid\n\n1. Introduction\nReal-time speech enhancement (SE) in bandwidth-limited binaural and distributed systems, such as hearing aids, must operate\nunder strict latency and computational constraints. Each device\nprocesses audio locally, exchanging only minimal information,\nwhich places strong limitations on model complexity and communication. Addressing SE under these joint constraints is essential for practical on-device deployment.\nOne line of research focuses on reducing the computational\ncost of on-device SE through neural model compression, typically combining structured pruning and quantization to reduce\nmemory use and computational complexity [1, 2, 3]. Hardwareoriented studies further show that not only the model’s sparsity level but also its structure critically impact the throughputmemory-quality trade-off on embedded platforms [4]. However, SE models are particularly sensitive to aggressive quantization due to their regression-based objectives, which amplifies quantization noise and hinders full integer deployment [5].\nThis has motivated the search for alternative solutions, such as\nhardware-aware mixed-precision inference [6] or distillationbased training strategies [7]. Complementary research explores\narchitectural efficiency: designing compact models that inherently require fewer operations. Grouped processing is attractive\nfor SE, where feature maps are partitioned into small groups and\nThis research was carried out with the support of the French National Research Agency as part of the REFINED project, “REal-time\nartiFicial INtelligence for hEaring aiDs” (ANR21-CE19-0043).\n\nprocessed in parallel by tiny sub-networks that periodically exchange information [8, 9]. Other works reduce input dimensionality by sub-sampling [10] or using an Equivalent Rectangular\nBandwidth (ERB)-scaled filterbank to compress the frequency\nrepresentations, as in GTCRN [11].\nDespite these advances, most efficiency-driven approaches\nfocus on single-microphone SE. In contrast, efficient multimicrophone methods remain comparatively underexplored,\neven though they can effectively exploit spatial cues for improved noise reduction. Recent works have begun to address this gap by proposing computationally efficient multimicrophone architectures, either by decoupling spatial and\nspectral processing [12] or by employing lightweight attention mechanisms to model spatial dependencies [13]. Nevertheless, these approaches typically incur higher computational\ncost than ultra-lightweight monaural models and often assume\na centralized processing with access to all microphone signals.\nIn practical binaural hearing-device systems, microphones are\ndistributed across physically separated nodes, and centralized\nprocessing would require continuous high-bandwidth wireless\ntransmission, which is infeasible under severe energy and bandwidth constraints. To address this limitation, fully distributed\nfusion-center-free signal processing frameworks have been explored to balance SE performance with bandwidth-efficient\ninter-device communication [14, 15].\nWhile prior work has demonstrated the feasibility of\nreduced-bandwidth distributed binaural SE [16], jointly achieving low latency and low computational complexity remains an\nopen challenge. To the best of our knowledge, no existing\napproach combines the required design elements within a distributed binaural framework under explicit real-time latency and\ncomputational constraints. This paper addresses this gap by introducing RT-Tango, a binaural SE framework specifically designed for real-time deployment on resource-constrained hearing devices. Concretely, our framework relies on the following\nefficiency-driven design choices:\n• Perceptually motivated feature compression using an ERBscaled filterbank, reducing input dimensionality while preserving speech-relevant cues.\n• Lightweight grouped recurrent mask estimation, enabling\nparallel and partitioned processing to reduce computational\ncost in distributed binaural settings.\n• Decoupled frequency resolution and algorithmic latency reduction through an asymmetric STFT configuration tailored\nfor streaming operations.\n• Temporal sparsification for real-time inference, including\nboth learned skip-RNN gating and fixed-rate frame reuse to\nreduce recurrent updates.\n\n\f2. Methodology\nRT-Tango revisits the Tango framework [16] from a systemlevel perspective. This redesign is motivated by the stringent\nconstraints of hearing aids, where strict causality, ultra-low latency, limited memory, and low-power embedded hardware are\ncritical requirements. Rather than introducing isolated optimizations, RT-Tango adopts complementary architectural and\nalgorithmic design principles detailed in the following sections.\n\nStage 1\n\nSTFT\nSTFT\n\nRear R\n\nRear L\n\nFront R\n\nFront L\n\nSTFT\nSTFT\n\nSN-DNN\nERB Features\n\nSN-DNN\nERB Features\n\nGRNN+FC\n\nGRNN+FC\n\nInv ERB\n\nInv ERB\n\nSDW-MWF\n\nSDW-MWF\n\n2.1. Baseline\nTango serves as our baseline due to its two-stage distributed architecture (illustrated in Figure 1) and proven effectiveness in\nspatially unconstrained microphone configurations [16]. Each\near-node independently estimates speech and noise masks using\na Single-Node DNN (SN-DNN) and computes a Speech Distortion Weighted Multichannel Wiener Filter (SDW-MWF) [17].\nThis produces an ear-specific compressed signal, which is transmitted to the contra-lateral ear-node. Then, a Multi-Node DNN\n(MN-DNN) refines the masks using both local signals and exchanged representations, from which a final SDW-MWF generates the enhanced binaural output. In its original formulation,\nhowever, the baseline imposes no latency or complexity constraints.\n2.2. Lightweight neural mask estimation\nTo reduce the computational cost of this distributed binaural\nprocessing, RT-Tango improves the efficiency in neural mask\nestimation by means of perceptually driven feature compression, grouped modeling of localized spectral dependencies, and\ntemporal sparsification, while preserving the characteristic twostage distributed spatial filtering framework of Tango.\n2.2.1. Feature compression\nThe ERB representation is used as the front-end for both neural mask estimation networks (indicated as SN-DNN and MNDNN in Figure 1). This perceptually motivated transformation\nreduces spectral resolution at high frequencies, where human\nauditory sensitivity is coarser, while preserving finer resolution\nat lower frequencies that carry most speech energy and cues. By\naligning the features with perceptual frequency scaling, ERB\ncompression reduces the input dimensionality of the mask estimators, lowering the number of parameters and operations in\nsubsequent layers. The estimated masks are then mapped back\nto the linear-frequency domain using an inverse ERB transformation to restore the spectral resolution required for filtering.\n2.2.2. Grouped RNN mask estimation\nThe mask estimation networks of RT-Tango implement a\ngrouped recurrent neural network (GRNN) to reduce computational complexity while preserving modeling capacity [18].\nThis choice is motivated by the localized nature of spectral\ndependencies in speech signals and the need to control recurrent computational complexity. Localized recurrent modeling within frequency sub-bands is consistent with common\nSE assumptions as spectral dependencies are typically stronger\nwithin nearby frequency regions. Since the computational\ncost of recurrent layers scales approximately quadratically as\nO(H 2 ) with the hidden state dimension H, partitioning the\nfeature space into G groups of size H/G, the total recurrent\ncomplexity becomes G · O((H/G)2 ) = O(H 2 /G), making\nit significantly lower compared to a full-band RNN. Although\n\nMN-DNN\nERB Features\n\nMN-DNN\nERB Features\n\nGRNN+FC\n\nGRNN+FC\n\nInv ERB\n\nInv ERB\n\nSDW-MWF\nStage 2\n\niSTFT\n\niSTFT\n\nOut R\n\nOut L\n\nSDW-MWF\n\nFigure 1: Block diagram of RT-Tango. It preserves Tango’s twostage processing scheme while introducing additional or modified modules focused on efficiency (highlighted in yellow) and\nlow-latency streaming (in italics).\n\nthe processing is performed independently within each group,\ncross-band dependencies are captured through a representation\nrearrangement mechanism [18], enabling cross-band information exchange and global spectral modeling.\n2.2.3. Temporal sparsification\nTo further reduce the computational load of high-rate real-time\nstreaming, RT-Tango exploits temporal redundancy in the input signal using skip inference strategies. Instead of performing a neural inference at every frame, the mask estimation networks reuse previously estimated masks when the input signal\nexhibits limited temporal variation. This temporal sparsification reduces the mask’s update frequency and thus the overall\ncomputational cost during streaming inference. In RT-Tango,\nwe define Fixed-Rate Skipping (FRS), as a strategy that executes the mask estimator at a predefined interval and reuses\npreviously estimated masks in between. We compare this with\nlearned skip gates [3, 19], where a gating mechanism dynamically decides whether to update the recurrent state at each frame\n(see Section 3.2.2).\n2.3. Low-latency streaming\nTo support low-latency streaming, we use an asymmetric STFT\nconfiguration [20, 21]. We use a long analysis window (aW)\nthat preserves the frequency resolution and a shorter synthesis window (sW) to reduce the reconstruction latency, enabling\nlow-latency real-time streaming. The spatial covariance matrices (SCM) required by the SDW-MWF are updated online using\na recursive exponential moving average (EMA). Under these\nstreaming constraints, the system operates as RT-Tango-OS.\n\n\fTable 1: Model comparison with left/right ear scores. Computational cost is reported in MMACs/s and decomposed into DNN and\nSDW-MWF components. A hop size of 16 ms corresponds to ≈ 62 STFT frames/s, while 4 ms corresponds to ≈ 250 STFT frames/s.\nSI-SAR is not reported for the unprocessed mixture, where no processing artifacts are present.\nSTFT\nModel\n\nHop\n\nTotal\n\nMMACs/s ↓\n\nSI-SIR ↑\n\nSI-SDR ↑\n\nSI-SAR ↑\n\nSTOI ↑\n\nPESQ ↑\n\nDNN\n\nL\n\nR\n\nL\n\nR\n\nL\n\nL\n\nL\n\nSDW-MWF\n\nR\n\nR\n\nR\n\n−\n\n−\n\n−\n\n−\n\n0.0\n\n−4.0\n\n−0.6\n\n−4.6\n\n−\n\n−\n\n0.68\n\n0.56\n\n1.14\n\n1.10\n\nTango\nGTCRN\nGTCRN\n\n16 ms\n16 ms\n4 ms\n\n605.98\n48.98\n197.5\n\n604.5\n48.98\n197.5\n\n1.48\n−\n−\n\n20.8\n16.1\n16.6\n\n24.1\n14.1\n13.8\n\n4.2\n5.6\n6.0\n\n4.4\n3.7\n4.0\n\n4.7\n6.4\n6.7\n\n4.7\n4.5\n5.0\n\n0.83\n0.76\n0.79\n\n0.84\n0.69\n0.71\n\n1.61\n1.47\n1.52\n\n1.64\n1.34\n1.36\n\nTango-RNN\n+ GRNNSN=8\nMN=2 ⋆\n\n16 ms\n16 ms\n\n67.20\n18.22\n\n65.72\n16.74\n\n1.48\n1.48\n\n21.6\n21.3\n\n25.0\n24.8\n\n4.7\n4.5\n\n5.0\n4.8\n\n5.2\n5.1\n\n5.2\n5.0\n\n0.84\n0.84\n\n0.85\n0.84\n\n1.66\n1.66\n\n1.70\n1.70\n\nRT-Tango (ours)\nRT-Tango-OS (ours)\n\n4 ms\n4 ms\n\n33.41\n35.14\n\n28.08\n28.08\n\n5.33\n7.01\n\n20.8\n20.5\n\n24.6\n24.7\n\n4.4\n2.9\n\n4.7\n3.8\n\n5.0\n3.4\n\n5.0\n4.0\n\n0.84\n0.80\n\n0.84\n0.82\n\n1.66\n1.54\n\n1.71\n1.63\n\nUnprocessed\n\n3. Experiments\n3.1. Experimental setup\nModels were trained on a simulated binaural dataset following the protocol of Monir et al. [22], which utilized a fourmicrophone hearing aid configuration with two microphones\nper ear. Clean speech from LibriSpeech [23] was mixed with\nspeech-shaped noise and real-world environmental noise. Evaluation was conducted on a subset of the BinauRec1 binaural\ndataset [24], comprising 1,200 mixtures generated using measured room impulse responses (RIRs) acquired using a portable\nhearing laboratory (PHL) [25] with behind-the-ear hearing aids\nmounted on a dummy head. We considered configurations\nwhere the target speech source was located in front and the noise\npositioned at 45◦ and 90◦ to the right of the target, respectively.\nThis results in a lower SIR at the right ear than at the left ear.\nDry signals are mixed at input SNRs of −5, 0, and 5 dB, before\nbeing convolved with the RIR.\nEnhancement performance was evaluated using scaleinvariant objective metrics (SI-SDR, SI-SIR, and SI-SAR), reported in dB [26], together with perceptual measures PESQ [27]\nand STOI [28]. Processing cost is reported in terms of MACs\neither per second or per frame, measured for one processing\nnode. Reported MACs include the DNN mask estimators, ERB\nand inverse-ERB transformations, and SDW-MWF processing,\nwhile FFT and iFFT operations are excluded.\nAlongside the original CNN-based Tango implementation,\nwe consider a causal variant, Tango-RNN, in which both the\nSN-DNN and MN-DNN are implemented using two stacked\nstateful RNN layers with 128 hidden units, followed by a fully\nconnected layer. We also include a lightweight neural baseline\nby adapting GTCRN [11] to the distributed setting, deploying\none instance per node. Each instance processes the four microphone signals as input and applies its estimated mask to the\nlocal reference channel, preserving a distributed per-node architecture.\nModels were implemented in PyTorch and trained with an\nAdam optimizer (lr = 10−3 ), by minimizing the mean squared\nerror between the estimated time–frequency mask and the target\nideal ratio mask. Training audio used a 32 ms STFT analysis\nwindow with a 16 ms hop for grouped ablations, FRS, and RTTango/RT-Tango-OS. For learned skipping and GTCRN (4 ms),\nthe hop was reduced to 4 ms to match RT-Tango’s frame rate.\nRT-Tango replaces the recurrent layers in Tango-RNN with\n1 Online: https://zenodo.org/records/7256984\n\nGRNNs to reduce its computational cost. We use G = 8 groups\nfor the SN-DNN and G = 2 groups for the MN-DNN. Temporal sparsification is implemented using FRS, with update rates\nof 1/4 for the SN-DNN and 1/2 for the MN-DNN, corresponding to one inference every four and two frames, respectively.\nAll results, except those obtained for RT-Tango-OS, were\ncomputed using SCMs estimated over entire utterances. RTTango-OS instead uses recursive SCM updates with a forgetting factor α = 0.995, applied every 8 frames at the 4 ms input\nrate, resulting in an effective update interval of 32 ms (≈ 31\nupdates/s). As online SCM estimation requires an adaptation\nperiod, RT-Tango-OS was evaluated in steady state by repeating each mixture a sufficient number of times to allow for convergence. The metrics are computed on the final repetition (see\nSection 3.2.4).\nTable 2: Ablation study on grouping strategies. The reported\nMMACs per frame are computed exclusively for the DNNs.\nDNN (SN+MN)\nModel\n\nSI-SDR\n\nSI-SAR\n\nMMACs / frame\n\nL\n\nR\n\nL\n\nR\n\nTango-RNN\n\n1.06\n\n4.7\n\n5.0\n\n5.2\n\n5.2\n\n+ GRNNSN=2\n+ GRNNSN=8\n\n0.69\n0.59\n\n4.7\n4.7\n\n4.9\n4.9\n\n5.2\n5.1\n\n5.2\n5.1\n\n+ GRNNMN=2\n+ GRNNMN=8\n\n0.74\n0.64\n\n4.7\n3.8\n\n4.9\n4.1\n\n5.2\n4.2\n\n5.1\n4.3\n\n3.2. Results\nIn Table 1, we report the results of RT-Tango and its streaming\nvariant RT-Tango-OS, and compare them to the Tango baseline,\nTango-RNN, and GTCRN. Compared to GTCRN, both Tango\nand Tango-RNN achieve consistently higher PESQ, STOI, and\nSI-SIR scores across both ears. Although GTCRN slightly outperforms them in SI-SDR and SI-SAR on the less noise-affected\nleft node, Tango-based approaches show a more balanced leftright behavior due to their two-stage mechanism. This interaural balance is particularly desirable in hearing-aid applications\nfor stable spatial perception and listening comfort.\nTango-RNN reduces Tango’s complexity to 67.2 MMAC/s,\nwhile RT-Tango reaches 33.4 MMAC/s despite operating at a\nhigher frame rate. Under identical conditions, RT-Tango is\nnearly six times more efficient than GTCRN (197.5 MMAC/s).\nThis robustness to compression stems from its hybrid architec-\n\n\fTable 3: Temporal sparsification in the SN-DNN of (⋆): performance and per-frame cost for updated (w/o skip) and nonupdated (w/skip) frames.\n\nTable 5: Effect of window length and type on enhancement performance, evaluated using RT-Tango.\nSI-SDR\n\nModel\n\nSI-SDR\n\nSI-SAR\n\naW\n\nsW\n\nWindow\n\nL\n\nR\n\nL\n\nR\n\nw/o Skip w/ Skip\n\nL\n\nR\n\nL\n\nR\n\n32\n\n32\n\nsqrtHann\n\n4.4\n\n4.7\n\n5.0\n\n5.0\n\n4.8\n\n5.1\n\n5.0\n\n32\n32\n32\n\n8\n8\n4\n\nsqrtHann\nasyHann\nasyHann\n\n1.2\n3.7\n3.4\n\n1.8\n4.3\n4.0\n\n1.4\n4.3\n3.9\n\n1.9\n4.5\n4.1\n\nSN-DNN of (⋆)\n\n0.09\n\n−\n\n4.5\n\n(⋆) + FRS 1/2\n(⋆) + FRS 1/4\n(⋆) + SkipRNN [19]\n(⋆) + TinyLSTM [3]\n\n0.09\n0.09\n0.09\n0.12\n\n0\n0\n0.01\n0.09\n\n4.4 4.7 5.1 5.0\n4.3 4.6 5.0 4.9\n4.4 4.3 5.0 4.6\n4.3 4.4 5.0 4.7\n\nTable 4: Temporal sparsification in the MN-DNN of (⋆): performance and per-frame cost for updated (w/o skip) and nonupdated (w/skip) frames.\n\nModel\n\nSI-SAR\n\nMMACs / frame\n\nMMACs / frame\n\nSI-SDR\n\nSI-SAR\n\nw/o Skip w/ Skip\n\nL\n\nR\n\nL\n\n4.8\n\n5.1 5.0\n\nR\n\nMN-DNN of (⋆)\n\n0.18\n\n−\n\n4.5\n\n(⋆) + FRS 1/2\n(⋆) + FRS 1/4\n(⋆) + SkipRNN [19]\n(⋆) + TinyLSTM [3]\n\n0.18\n0.18\n0.18\n0.21\n\n0\n0\n0.02\n0.07\n\n4.4 4.8 5.1 5.1\n4.3 4.8 4.8 5.0\n3.8 4.7 4.5 5.0\n3.3 4.6 3.9 4.8\n\nture, where neural networks guide the spatial filter rather than\ndirectly reconstructing the signal.\nRT-Tango-OS enables strictly causal streaming with an algorithmic latency of 8 ms, through the asymmetric STFT and\nonline SDW-MWF updates, resulting in a slight but expected\nperformance degradation relative to offline RT-Tango. RTTango-OS requires 0.49 MMACs per frame (0.27 MMACs\nfor the DNN and 0.22 MMACs for the SDW-MWF update).\nWith the proposed temporal sparsification, it corresponds to\n35.14 MMACs/s at ≈250 frames/s. Without sparsification\n(not reported here), the computational cost would reach 124\nMMACs/s. The RT-Tango-OS configuration results from the\nprogressive design choices described in Section 2, whose individual contributions are analyzed in the ablation studies below.\n3.2.1. Impact of Grouped Recurrent Modeling\nGrouping applied independently to SN-DNN and MN-DNN reveals different behaviors (Table 2). Grouping the SN-DNN significantly reduces cost with negligible impact on quality. Using 8 groups on SN-DNN lowers the total DNN (SN+MN)\ncomplexity from 1.06 to 0.59 MMAC/frame while maintaining\nSI-SDR at 4.7/4.9 dB and preserving PESQ/STOI. In contrast,\nMN-DNN is more sensitive to grouping. While MN=2-GRNN\npreserves performance, MN=8-GRNN degrades SI-SDR and\nSI-SAR by around 0.8-1 dB. These results justify the combined\ngrouping strategy (SN=8, MN=2), marked with (⋆) in Table 1.\n3.2.2. Effect of temporal sparsification via skip inference\nTables 3 and 4 evaluate temporal sparsification for the SNDNN and MN-DNN stages. For SN-DNN, FRS preserves performance within 0.2 dB of the baseline for both 1/2 and 1/4\nconfigurations while eliminating computation on non-updated\nframes. Learned skipping relies on a gating mechanism that\nmust be evaluated at every frame, introducing additional MACs.\nLearned skipping achieves an effective skip ratio of 80%, but\n\nstill introduces minor degradation, primarily on the right channel. The MN-DNN is more sensitive to learned skipping; it\nreduces SI-SDR from 4.5 dB to 3.8 dB (SkipRNN [19]) and\n3.3 dB (TinyLSTM [3]) on the left channel, whereas FRS maintains performance within 0.2 dB of the baseline. Given its stability and predictable computational savings, FRS is adopted in\nthe RT-Tango configuration (SN 1/4, MN 1/2), corresponding\nto 75% frame skipping in the SN-DNN and 50% in the MNDNN. At a 4 ms hop rate, this reduces the DNN cost from 67.5\nMMACs/s without sparsification to 28.08 MMACs/s.\n3.2.3. Analysis of the latency-quality trade-off\nTable 5 analyzes the impact of reducing the synthesis window\nwhile keeping the analysis window fixed at 32 ms. These results are computed with batch (offline) SCMs to isolate the effect of the STFT configuration from online SCM estimation.\nStandard square-root Hann windows degrade rapidly at short\nsynthesis lengths. In contrast, the asymmetric Hann [21] configuration maintains better SI-SDR and SI-SAR at low latencies. An 8 ms synthesis window offers the most favorable compromise between delay and SE quality. Reducing the synthesis\nwindow to 4 ms further decreases latency but results in performance degradation. We therefore select the 8 ms asymmetric\nHann synthesis window for RT-Tango-OS.\n3.2.4. Online SCM matrix estimation and convergence\nAs can be seen in Table 1, RT-Tango-OS achieves an SI-SIR\ncomparable to the offline RT-Tango. However, due to the constraints imposed by low-latency streaming, the SI-SDR and SISAR show a slight decrease. This performance gap is first introduced by the asymmetric STFT configuration (Section 3.2.3),\nand is then amplified by the requirements of online SCM estimation. Despite this, RT-Tango-OS maintains STOI and PESQ\nvalues close to GTCRN at the same high frame rate, while still\nbeing significantly more computationally efficient. This indicates that although strictly online SCM estimation affects reconstruction, the resulting speech intelligibility and perceived\nquality remain competitive with our baselines.\n\n4. Conclusions\nThis paper introduced RT-Tango, a distributed binaural SE\nframework designed to satisfy the stringent real-time, latency,\nand computational constraints of modern hearing devices. By\nrevisiting the Tango architecture through complementary architectural and signal-processing optimizations, RT-Tango significantly reduces computational complexity while preserving enhancement performance and interaural balance. In addition, RTTango-OS, its strictly causal streaming variant, operates with an\nalgorithmic latency of 8 ms, makes RT-Tango particularly well\nsuited for practical deployment in modern binaural hearing aids.\n\n\f5. Generative AI Use Disclosure\nThe authors used AI tools solely for language editing and clarity improvement. All scientific ideas, content, and results were\ndeveloped and verified by the authors.\n\n6. References\n[1] K. Tan and D. Wang, “Towards Model Compression for Deep\nLearning Based Speech Enhancement,” IEEE/ACM Transactions\non Audio, Speech, and Language Processing, vol. 29, pp. 1785–\n1794, 2021.\n[2] J.-Y. Wu, C. Yu, S.-W. Fu, C.-T. Liu, S.-Y. Chien, and Y. Tsao,\n“Increasing Compactness of Deep Learning Based Speech Enhancement Models With Parameter Pruning and Quantization\nTechniques,” IEEE Signal Processing Letters, vol. 26, no. 12, pp.\n1887–1891, 2019.\n[3] I. Fedorov, M. Stamenovic, C. Jensen, L.-C. Yang, A. Mandell,\nY. Gan, M. Mattina, and P. N. Whatmough, “TinyLSTMs: Efficient Neural Speech Enhancement for Hearing Aids,” in Interspeech, 2020, pp. 4054–4058.\n[4] M. Stamenovic, N. L. Westhausen, L.-C. Yang, C. Jensen, and\nA. Pawlicki, “Weight, Block or Unit? Exploring Sparsity Tradeoffs for Speech Enhancement on Tiny Neural Accelerators,” in\nNeurIPS Workshop on Efficient Natural Language and Speech\nProcessing (NeurIPS ENLSP), 2021.\n[5] E. Cohen, H. V. Habi, and A. Netzer, “Towards Fully Quantized Neural Networks For Speech Enhancement,” in Interspeech,\n2023, pp. 181–185.\n[6] M. Rusci, M. Fariselli, M. Croome, F. Paci, and E. Flamand,\n“Accelerating RNN-based Speech Enhancement on a Multi-Core\nMCU with Mixed FP16-INT8 Post-Training Quantization,” in\nEuropean Conference on Machine Learning and Principles and\nPractice of Knowledge Discovery in Databases (ECML PKDD),\n2022, pp. 606–617.\n[7] E. Cohen, H. V. Habi, R. Peretz, and A. Netzer, “Fully Quantized\nNeural Networks for Audio Source Separation,” IEEE Open Journal of Signal Processing, vol. 5, pp. 926–933, 2024.\n[8] K. Tan and D. Wang, “Learning Complex Spectral Mapping With\nGated Convolutional Recurrent Networks for Monaural Speech\nEnhancement,” IEEE/ACM Transactions on Audio, Speech, and\nLanguage Processing, vol. 28, pp. 380–390, 2020.\n[9] Y. Luo, C. Han, and N. Mesgarani, “Ultra-Lightweight Speech\nSeparation Via Group Communication,” in IEEE International\nConference on Audio, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP),\n2021, pp. 16–20.\n[10] Z.-Q. Wang, S. Cornell, S. Choi, Y. Lee, B.-Y. Kim, and S. Watanabe, “FNeural Speech Enhancement with Very Low Algorithmic\nLatency and Complexity via Integrated full- and sub-band Modeling,” in IEEE International Conference on Audio, Speech and\nSignal Processing (ICASSP), 2023, pp. 1–5.\n[11] X. Rong, T. Sun, X. Zhang, Y. Hu, C. Zhu, and J. Lu, “GTCRN: A\nSpeech Enhancement Model Requiring Ultralow Computational\nResources,” in IEEE International Conference on Audio, Speech\nand Signal Processing (ICASSP), 2024, pp. 971–975.\n[12] A. Pandey and J. Azcarreta, “Ultra low-compute complex spectral masking for multichannel speech enhancement,” in IEEE International Conference on Audio, Speech and Signal Processing\n(ICASSP), 2025, pp. 1–5.\n[13] Y. Zhang, H. Pei, W. Wang, and G. Huang, “LMFCA-Net: A\nLightweight Model for Multi-Channel Speech Enhancement with\nEfficient Narrow-Band and Cross-Band Attention,” in IEEE International Conference on Audio, Speech and Signal Processing\n(ICASSP), 2025, pp. 1–5.\n[14] A. Bertrand and M. Moonen, “Distributed Adaptive NodeSpecific Signal Estimation in Fully Connected Sensor Networks—Part II: Simultaneous and Asynchronous Node Updating,” IEEE Transactions on Signal Processing, vol. 58, no. 10,\npp. 5292–5306, 2010.\n\n[15] S. Doclo, M. Moonen, T. Van den Bogaert, and J. Wouters,\n“Reduced-Bandwidth and Distributed MWF-Based Noise Reduction Algorithms for Binaural Hearing Aids,” IEEE Transactions\non Audio, Speech, and Language Processing, vol. 17, no. 1, pp.\n38–51, 2009.\n[16] N. Furnon, R. Serizel, S. Essid, and I. Illina, “DNN-Based Mask\nEstimation for Distributed Speech Enhancement in Spatially Unconstrained Microphone Arrays,” IEEE/ACM Transactions on Audio, Speech, and Language Processing, vol. 29, pp. 2310–2323,\n2021.\n[17] S. Doclo, A. Spriet, J. Wouters, and M. Moonen, “Frequencydomain criterion for the speech distortion weighted multichannel\nwiener filter for robust noise reduction,” Speech Communication,\nvol. 49, no. 7–8, p. 636–656, Jul. 2007.\n[18] F. Gao, L. Wu, L. Zhao, T. Qin, X. Cheng, and T.-Y. Liu, “Efficient Sequence Learning with Group Recurrent Networks,” in\nProceedings of the 2018 Conference of the North American Chapter of the Association for Computational Linguistics: Human Language Technologies, Volume 1 (Long Papers), M. Walker, H. Ji,\nand A. Stent, Eds., Jun. 2018, pp. 799–808.\n[19] V. Campos, B. Jou, X. G. i Nieto, J. Torres, and S.-F. Chang,\n“Skip RNN: Learning to Skip State Updates in Recurrent Neural\nNetworks,” in International Conference on Learning Representations, 2018.\n[20] Z.-Q. Wang, G. Wichern, S. Watanabe, and J. Le Roux, “Stftdomain neural speech enhancement with very low algorithmic latency,” IEEE/ACM Transactions on Audio, Speech, and Language\nProcessing, vol. 31, pp. 397–410, 2023.\n[21] S. U. N. Wood and J. Rouat, “Unsupervised Low Latency Speech\nEnhancement With RT-GCC-NMF,” IEEE Journal of Selected\nTopics in Signal Processing, vol. 13, no. 2, p. 332–346, May 2019.\n[22] N.-E. Monir, P. Magron, and R. Serizel, “Frequency-Weighted\nTraining Losses for Phoneme-Level DNN-based Speech Enhancement,” in IEEE International Workshop on Multimedia Signal Processing (MMSP), 2025, pp. 310–315.\n[23] V. Panayotov, G. Chen, D. Povey, and S. Khudanpur, “Librispeech: An ASR corpus based on public domain audio books,”\nin IEEE International Conference on Audio, Speech and Signal\nProcessing (ICASSP), 2015, pp. 5206–5210.\n[24] L. Delebecque and R. Serizel, “BinauRec: A dataset to test the influence of the use of room impulse responses on binaural speech\nenhancement,” in European Signal Processing Conference (EUSIPCO), 2023, pp. 126–130.\n[25] C. Pavlovic, R. Kassayan, S. R. Prakash, H. Kayser, V. Hohmann,\nand A. Atamaniuk, “A high-fidelity multi-channel portable platform for development of novel algorithms for assistive listening\nwearables,” The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America, vol.\n146, pp. 2878–2878, 2019.\n[26] J. L. Roux, S. Wisdom, H. Erdogan, and J. R. Hershey, “SDR\n– Half-baked or Well Done?” in IEEE International Conference\non Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP), 2019, pp.\n626–630.\n[27] A. Rix, J. Beerends, M. Hollier, and A. Hekstra, “Perceptual evaluation of speech quality (PESQ)-a new method for speech quality\nassessment of telephone networks and codecs,” in IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech, and Signal Processing\n(ICASSP), vol. 2, 2001, pp. 749–752.\n[28] C. H. Taal, R. C. Hendriks, R. Heusdens, and J. Jensen, “A shorttime objective intelligibility measure for time-frequency weighted\nnoisy speech,” in IEEE International Conference on Acoustics,\nSpeech and Signal Processing (ICASSP), 2010, pp. 4214–4217.\n\n\f", "numLines": 871, "startLine": 1, "totalLines": 871}}}
